			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Need everyones help to change this<a name="34445"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Apr 13 04 1:31 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Although it sucks to have to loose something you spent a long time on, there's an easy solution - be careful what you augment.  
<br />

<br />
I spent a lot of points on Malevolent armor and aug'ed 'em with bard augs.  It's probably NEVER going to leave my body... ever!  And, even though I've seen better, I keep what I have.  I don't necessarily like it, but it's important.
<br />

<br />
WHY?
<br />

<br />
Augs are just like no drop items.  The higher end gear is almost ALL no drop. So, you could make exactly the same argument you made for augs about no drop items.  
<br />

<br />
However, what you'd be missing is that no drop items prevent mudflation.  There is almost no risk in releasing a no drop All/All +200 hp item in a uberly high end zone.  Even if they made it drop on every mob in the zone, there's still no risk.  Players that should get it will and lvl 10 twink beeserkers won't.
<br />

<br />
But, as soon as they take the no drop flag off, it becomes trash.  And, that hurts you, whether you realize it or not.  Consider the Greatstaff of thunder.  For wars, it's an absolutely amazing weapon.  When it first appeared, it was the hottest ticket on the market.  At 100 pp in the bazarre, it holds agro better than anything 500 times it's cost.  Heck, you could almost say it's broken...   
<br />

<br />
I'm equating 'droppable' to 'sell-back-able augments'.  It's a very similar argument and one that requires you to distance yourself from your plight to grasp.  We all get stung by it, but it's better for the game in the long run by preventing mudflation and trivialization of content. It's right in the same way that recommended levels is.
<br />

<br />
Wyndaria.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
